WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.129 --> 00:00:03.029
Recognizing survival responses in behavior,

1
00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:05.289
looking beyond the reaction.

2
00:00:06.619 --> 00:00:07.880
You may have seen this

3
00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:11.149
A young person reacts quickly.

4
00:00:11.489 --> 00:00:12.909
They raise their voice.

5
00:00:13.329 --> 00:00:14.170
They walk out.

6
00:00:14.949 --> 00:00:16.799
Or they just shut down completely

7
00:00:17.709 --> 00:00:18.850
and in that moment,

8
00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:20.729
it can feel like a choice,

9
00:00:21.229 --> 00:00:22.329
like they're being difficult,

10
00:00:23.069 --> 00:00:24.809
like they're refusing to engage.

11
00:00:26.079 --> 00:00:27.290
But think about this.

12
00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.780
What if they're not choosing that behavior at all?

13
00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:34.659
What if their body is reacting before they've had time to think?

14
00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:37.610
Because that's what survival responses are.

15
00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:40.860
When the people we support feel unsafe,

16
00:00:41.009 --> 00:00:43.509
or even just perceive something as unsafe,

17
00:00:43.930 --> 00:00:46.040
their body can move straight into fight,

18
00:00:46.369 --> 00:00:46.750
flight,

19
00:00:46.970 --> 00:00:47.750
or freeze.

20
00:00:48.529 --> 00:00:50.150
And it happens fast,

21
00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:51.909
faster than thinking,

22
00:00:52.409 --> 00:00:53.830
faster than reasoning.

23
00:00:54.169 --> 00:00:55.970
So what you see on the outside,

24
00:00:56.330 --> 00:00:57.159
the aggression,

25
00:00:57.369 --> 00:00:58.240
the avoidance,

26
00:00:58.409 --> 00:00:59.290
the shutdown.

27
00:01:00.009 --> 00:01:02.869
Is actually the body trying to protect itself.

28
00:01:03.860 --> 00:01:06.730
Now this is where things often go wrong in practice.

29
00:01:07.209 --> 00:01:08.459
We see the behavior.

30
00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:11.139
And we respond to the behavior.

31
00:01:11.430 --> 00:01:12.480
We challenge it,

32
00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:13.690
we question it.

33
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.860
We try to regain control of the situation,

34
00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:20.459
but if that young person is already in a survival response.

35
00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:24.260
They're not able to process that in the way we expect.

36
00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:27.120
So instead of calming things down,

37
00:01:27.819 --> 00:01:30.099
We can unintentionally escalate it.

38
00:01:30.849 --> 00:01:34.730
What this means in practice is recognizing the signs early.

39
00:01:35.089 --> 00:01:37.080
You might notice a change in tone.

40
00:01:37.410 --> 00:01:39.029
Body language shifts,

41
00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:40.730
they become more alert

42
00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:42.129
or more withdrawn.

43
00:01:43.029 --> 00:01:46.480
That's the point where you've got the best chance to respond differently,

44
00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:49.230
because once they're fully in that response.

45
00:01:50.069 --> 00:01:51.910
It's not about reasoning anymore.

46
00:01:52.309 --> 00:01:53.430
It's about safety.

47
00:01:54.449 --> 00:01:56.940
Think about a time when you felt under pressure.

48
00:01:57.849 --> 00:02:00.230
Your reaction probably wasn't calm

49
00:02:00.379 --> 00:02:02.190
or carefully thought through.

50
00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:04.269
Now imagine that feeling,

51
00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:05.809
but stronger

52
00:02:06.169 --> 00:02:07.610
and happening more often.

53
00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:11.020
That's what some of the people we support are dealing with.

54
00:02:11.669 --> 00:02:14.009
Behavior is often communication,

55
00:02:14.389 --> 00:02:17.050
and survival responses are the body saying,

56
00:02:17.509 --> 00:02:19.110
I don't feel safe right now.

57
00:02:19.850 --> 00:02:21.770
So what does good practice look like?

58
00:02:22.009 --> 00:02:24.029
It means slowing things down,

59
00:02:24.449 --> 00:02:26.190
keeping your tone steady,

60
00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:28.830
avoiding confrontation where possible,

61
00:02:29.490 --> 00:02:31.250
giving space when it's needed.

62
00:02:32.009 --> 00:02:33.550
Not ignoring behavior,

63
00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:36.649
but responding in a way that reduces threat.

64
00:02:37.449 --> 00:02:37.460
Because

65
00:02:37.850 --> 00:02:40.210
the moment you reduce that sense of danger.

66
00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:45.089
The young person has a chance to come back into a place where they can think again.

67
00:02:45.889 --> 00:02:48.050
And that's when things start to shift.

68
00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:50.710
From a safeguarding point of view,

69
00:02:51.089 --> 00:02:52.009
this is crucial.

70
00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:55.259
If we misunderstand survival responses,

71
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.559
We can increase risk without meaning to.

72
00:02:59.259 --> 00:03:00.710
But when we recognize them,

73
00:03:01.399 --> 00:03:03.039
We reduce escalation,

74
00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:04.899
we support regulation,

75
00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:08.639
and we create environments where young people feel safer.

76
00:03:09.369 --> 00:03:11.149
And when people feel safer,

77
00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:12.770
they behave differently.